      "we need to prove this theorem. Let's think about how to approach this.\n\nWe need to show that `L.flatten.take i` equals `(L.take j).flatten ++ (L[j]?.getD []).take k`.\n\nLet's think about the structure of `L.flatten` and `L.flatten.take i`. `L.flatten` is the concatenation of all sublists in `L`. `L.flatten.take i` is the first `i` elements of this concatenated list.\n\nNow, let's analyze the right-hand side of the equation:\n- `L.take j` is the list of the first `j` sublists of `L`.\n- `(L.take j).flatten` is the concatenation of these first `j` sublists.\n- `L[j]?.getD []` is the `j`-th sublist of `L` (if `j < L.length`, otherwise `[]`).\n- `(L[j]?.getD []).take k` is the first `k` elements of this `j`-th sublist (if `j < L.length`, otherwise `[]`).\n\nSo, the right-hand side is `(L.take j).flatten ++ (L[j]?.getD []).take k`.\n\nTo prove the equality, we need to show that the first `i` elements of `L.flatten` can be constructed by concatenating:\n1. The concatenation of the first `j` sublists (`(L.take j).flatten`).\n2. The first `k` elements of the `j`-th sublist (`(L[j]?.getD []).take k`).\n\nwhere `j` is the index of the first sublist whose cumulative length exceeds `i`, and `k` is `i` minus the length of the first `j` sublists.\n\nLet's think about how to prove this.\n\nWe can use induction on `L`. The theorem is stated for an arbitrary `L : List (List α)` and `i : Nat`.\n\nBase case: `L = []`. Then `L.flatten = []`, so `L.flatten.take i = []`. The right side is `(take j []).flatten ++ (j < 0 ? [] : ...).take k = [] ++ [] = []`. So both sides are equal.\n\nInductive step: Assume `L = l :: L'`. We need to prove the theorem for `L` assuming it holds for `L'`.\n\nLet's think about `L.flatten` and `L.flatten.take i`. `L.flatten` is `l ++ L'.flatten`. `L.flatten.take i` is `take i (l ++ L'.flatten)`.\n\nWe need to show that this equals `(L.take j).flatten ++ (L[j]?.getD []).take k`.\n\nTo do this, we need to determine `j` and `k` in terms of `l` and `L'`.\n\n`j` is `(map length L).partialSums.findIdx (· > i) - 1`. `map length L` is `map length (l :: L')` which is `length l :: map length L'`. `partialSums` of this is `length l :: (length l + map length L').partialSums`.\n\nSo, `j` is `((map length L').partialSums ++ [length l]).findIdx (fun x => x > i) - 1`.\n\nSimilarly, `k` is `i - (L.take j).flatten.length`.\n\nThis seems complicated, so we need a strategy.\n\nPerhaps we can reason about the length of `L.flatten` and the lengths of the sublists.\n\nAlternatively, we can use the fact that `L.flatten` is the concatenation of the sublists, and `L.flatten.take i` is the first `i` elements of this concatenation.\n\nLet's look at the structure of the proof in the given context. There's an induction on `L` in the proof of `getElem_flatten`. Maybe we can use a similar approach here.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\n\n/-! ### flatten -/\n\ntheorem length_flatten_mem_partialSums_map_length (L : List (List α)) :\n    L.flatten.length ∈ (L.map length).partialSums := by\n  induction L with\n  | nil => simp\n  | cons l L ih =>\n    simp [flatten_cons, partialSums_cons]\n    right\n    simpa using ih\n\ntheorem getElem_flatten_aux₁ (L : List (List α)) (i : Nat) (h : i < L.flatten.length) :\n    (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (· > i) - 1 < L.length := by\n  have := findIdx_lt_length_of_exists (xs := (L.map length).partialSums) (p := fun x => decide (x > i))\n  specialize this ⟨L.flatten.length,\n    length_flatten_mem_partialSums_map_length L, by grind⟩\n  simp at this\n  simp\n  have : 0 < findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums := by\n    by_contra w\n    simp at w\n  omega\n\ntheorem getElem_flatten_aux₂ (L : List (List α)) (i : Nat) (h : i < L.flatten.length) :\n    let j := (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (· > i) - 1\n    have hj : j < L.length := getElem_flatten_aux₁ L i h\n    let k := i - (L.take j).flatten.length\n    k < L[j].length := sorry\n\n/--\nIndexing into a flattened list: `L.flatten[i]`